3.  Dry disconnect hoses with fail-close valves to prevent product from flowing from the bulk container in case of equipment or power failure.
4.  Six-inch concrete curbing around the entire facility perimeter;
5.  Emergency valve to prevent storm water, fire-fighting water or chemical released in an emergency situation from traveling off-site;
6.  High volumewater and foam fire fighting system in the product unloading area, designed to extinguish fires and suppress fumes from releases;
7.  Emergency alarm system monitored 24 hours per dat, sever days per week by response unit of neighboring company.

FIVE YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY.

There Have been no releases of regulated chemicals, in reportable quantities, since packaging operations began in October, 1998.

ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM.

The primary methods for generating recommendations are through periodic review and/or revision of Process Hazard Analyses (PHAs), incident investigations and operational procedures review (Management of Change). These reviews provide a means for continuous improvement.

To further reduce the likelihood of an accidental release, an extensive review program has been established for all system components and operating parameters.  This includes a daily briefing on  materials being handled, required procedures, PPE and associated equipment, monthly and annual inspection and maintenance schedule that is rigidly followed, ensuring a well?maintained physical plant.

